## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+. `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. The replacement is **cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken`.

### Key Paradigm Shift

| .NET Framework (preemptive) | .NET 8 (cooperative) |
|---|---|
| Runtime forcibly injects `ThreadAbortException` | Code must **voluntarily check** for cancellation |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}

// Usage:
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    // Check the token at regular intervals in long-running work
    for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // ... do a unit of work ...
    }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

### If You Can't Modify the Work Delegate

If `work` is opaque code you can't inject a token into (e.g., third-party library call), cancellation **cannot** stop it cooperatively. Two options:

**Option A — Fire-and-forget the runaway task** (thread leaks until work finishes naturally):
```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    if (task.Wait(timeout))
        return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();

    // Task keeps running — thread is NOT killed
    throw new TimeoutException(
        $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
}
```

**Option B — Move work to a child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. This is the only way to truly terminate uncooperative code in modern .NET.

### Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Fix |
|---|---|
| Adding `CancellationToken` param but never checking it | Insert `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at loop checkpoints |
| Not passing the token through the full call chain | Every method in the chain must forward the token |
| Expecting the token to interrupt `Thread.Sleep` | Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Always wrap in `using` — leaks timers otherwise |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it | Let it propagate; only catch at the orchestration boundary |
| Assuming cancellation is instant | It only fires at the next `ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` checkpoint |

The critical takeaway: **there is no .NET 8 equivalent to forcibly killing a thread**. The work must cooperate by checking the token. Design checkpoint frequency based on your acceptable cancellation latency.
